"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082305","Treasury","false","2019-03-13","<p>Employers normally incur expenditure on employee healthcare for a business purpose and can deduct this when calculating the employer’s own taxable profits.</p><p>However, from 1 January 2015, the Government also exempted any benefit in kind or payment of earnings, up to an annual cap of £500 per employee, from a charge to income tax when an employer meets the cost of recommended medical treatment. There is also a corresponding National Insurance contributions disregard.</p><p>Medical treatment is recommended where it is provided in accordance with a recommendation from an occupational health service in order to help an employee return to work after a period of absence due to ill-health or injury. The 28 consecutive day qualifying period makes sure that the tax exemption is targeted at those cases in greatest need of support. Evidence showed that sickness absence cases lasting four weeks or longer were at the greatest risk of turning into long term cases.</p><p>The Government ensured that this exemption would be easy to understand and administer, so employers do not need to inform HMRC about payments for treatments covered by the £500 per employee per year limit. This means that information is not available to assess the direct impact of the exemption. However, the Government estimated in 2014 that employees working for approximately 10,000 businesses each year would benefit and Table 2.2 of Budget 2014 set out the expected cost to the Exchequer of £20 million per annum by 2018-19.</p><p>The Government keeps all taxes under review.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","228637 ; 228638","2019-03-13T16:38:16.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082305/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082305/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-05","Medical Treatments: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has any plans to amend the Income Tax (Recommended Medical Treatment) Regulations 2014 to incentivise employers to support staff returning to work after a period of sickness absence; and what assessment he has made of the effect of the 28 consecutive day qualifying period on the number of staff returning to work.","false","Biography information for Martin Vickers","Cleethorpes","Martin Vickers","228639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082306","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-13","<p>The tax incentives available to employers to encourage investment in employee health and wellbeing include relief for employer-funded medical treatment up to £500 where there has been a recommendation from an occupational health professional and the employee has been absent for 28 days.</p><p> </p><p>To inform future policy decisions, the Government is supporting the West Midlands Combined Authority to undertake a pilot study to assess whether and how financial incentives affect SME actions to improve health and wellbeing in the workplace.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will consult this year on measures to encourage and support all employers to reduce health-related job loss, and to improve access to occupational health.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2019-03-13T14:45:57.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082306/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082306/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Occupational Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent financial incentives she has introduced to encourage employers to invest in the health and well being of their workforce through the contracting of services designed to facilitate more rapid returns to work by employees at risk of health-related job loss.","false","Biography information for Martin Vickers","Cleethorpes","Martin Vickers","228640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082307","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-11","<p>The Department is considering a range of options for consulting on Healthy Start vouchers. The consultation has been postponed until after European Union exit, when we will be in a better position to identify opportunities to improve the Healthy Start Scheme.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-03-11T14:03:53.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082307/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082307/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Healthy Start Scheme: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the timeframe is for the public consultation on the healthy start welfare food scheme, announced in the paper entitled, Childhood Obesity: A plan for action, published in June 2018.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","228641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082308","Department for Education","false","2019-03-11","<p>The information requested is not held centrally because our system for recording correspondence to my right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State logs cases by number and name and does not fully capture the category of complainant.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-03-11T14:11:56.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082308/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082308/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Specialist Schools: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2019 to Question 225521 on Specialist Schools: Complaints, how many complaints he has received from parents in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","228738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082309","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-13","<p><strong></strong>Data on the number of children recorded as obese in England, each region and each London Borough aged four to five years and aged 10 to 11 years, are attached.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-03-13T12:32:22.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082309/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082309/answer","Table 1_Number of children aged 4-5 years measured in the National Child Measurement Programme (NCMP) in the obese category.docx ; Table 2_Number of children aged 10-11 years measured in the National Child Measurement Programme (NCMP) in the obese category.docx","Table 1_Number of children aged 4-5 years measured in the National Child Measurement Programme (NCMP) in the obese category.docx ; Table 2_Number of children aged 10-11 years measured in the National Child Measurement Programme (NCMP) in the obese category.docx","PQ228739 attached table ; PQ228739 attached table","PQ228739 attached table ; PQ228739 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082309/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many children aged (a) four to five and (b) 10 to 11 years were recorded as obese in (i) England, (ii) each English region and (iii) each London borough in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","228739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082310","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-13","<p>The Healthy Start and Nursery Milk schemes are demand led statutory schemes. This means that the Department must meet expenditure arising from legitimate claims made in line with the legislation. Funding is allocated to the schemes to meet the actual demand, rising or falling in line with the overall uptake for each scheme, and the Government works to ensure that eligible people are aware of the schemes and how they can benefit from them.</p><p> </p><p>The funding allocated to the schemes is accounted for through a single cost centre with total costs is shown in the following table. A split by individual scheme is not available in the format requested.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010 - 2011</p></td><td><p>£133,996,866</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011 - 2012</p></td><td><p>£139,569,214</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012 - 2013</p></td><td><p>£141,366,339</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 2014</p></td><td><p>£137,790,212</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 2015</p></td><td><p>£128,904,379</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 - 2016</p></td><td><p>£124,890,649</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 - 2017</p></td><td><p>£112,556,870</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017 - 2018</p></td><td><p>£104,709,791</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Audited spend data for the 2018-19 financial year is not yet available.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","228714","2019-03-13T12:25:58.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082310/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082310/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Healthy Start Scheme: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much funding his Department has allocated to healthy start welfare foods payments in each year since 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","228740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082311","Women and Equalities","false","2019-03-12","<p>100% of employers believed to be in scope of the regulations reported their figures by August 2018.</p><p> </p><p>It is an employer’s legal responsibility to ensure that they report on time and that their figures are accurate. The vast majority of the over 10,500 that reported last year have completed the calculations correctly. In 2018, the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) commenced enforcement action against 100 employers suspected of publishing inaccurate gender pay gap figures.</p><p> </p><p>The EHRC enforcement found that they were a result of errors, rather than a deliberate attempt to mislead. They have worked closely with employers to identify and correct errors - all of whom have now either verified their figures or identified and corrected calculation errors.</p><p> </p><p>Employers have until 30 March, for the public sector, and 4 April, for the private and voluntary sector, to submit their data for the second year. The data for the 2018-19 reporting year will be reviewed once the deadline has passed.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","228616 ; 228617 ; 228618","2019-03-12T10:33:37.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082311/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082311/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2019-03-05","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether there are companies that have not filed their gender pay gap data for 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","228642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082312","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-11","<p>School nurses are commissioned by local authorities and can be employed by a range of provider organisations including health trusts and local authorities themselves. Data collections are by National Health Service electronic staff record (ESR) which does not cover the complete range of these organisations. As a result, it is not possible to provide accurate data on the total size of the school nurse workforce.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the number of full-time equivalent school nurses held on the NHS ESR record are attached.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-03-11T14:06:38.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082312/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082312/answer","Table 1 - Full-time equivalent (fte) school nurses each month since June 2010.docx","Table 1 - Full-time equivalent (fte) school nurses each month since June 2010.docx","PQ228741 attached table","PQ228741 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082312/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Nurses: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many full-time equivalent school nurses there were in each month since June 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","228741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082313","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-12","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 31 January 2019 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2019-01-23/211756/" target="_blank">211756</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-03-12T12:40:05.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082313/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082313/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Accidents: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many falls among people aged 65 and over led to a hospital admission in each year since 2009-10; and what the five most frequent types of those falls were.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","228742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082314","Department for Education","false","2019-03-13","<p>The independent panel will report shortly. The government will then conclude the overall review later this year.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-03-13T16:54:36.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082314/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082314/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Higher Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when he plans to publish the review of post-18 education and funding.","true","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","228643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082315","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-13","<p>Research with claimants who have recently undergone a Work Capability Assessment is undertaken by a different organisation to the provider delivering the assessments. The telephone survey is voluntary and is based on a set of questions agreed with the department.</p><p>The Department also undertakes its own survey which is designed to monitor claimant satisfaction with the services offered by the department and to enable claimant views to inform improvements to the delivery of benefits and services. This information is published on gov.uk.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2019-03-13T15:18:28.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082315/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082315/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Disabled People of 22 January 2019, Official Report, column 106WH on the satisfaction ratings of disability benefit claimants, if she will commission independent research on the satisfaction rates of claimants who have recently undergone a work capability assessment.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","228788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082316","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-13","<p>The British Medical Association and the Royal College of General Practitioners agreed to the revised wording of the ESA65B on 4 August 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is committed to ensuring all of its communications are clear, accurate and understandable and we continuously improve our letters. We engage regularly with the welfare benefits advice sector and disability charities and take into account all of the feedback we receive.</p><p> </p><p>We have received comments from a number of sources including MPs, stakeholder organisations and GPs on the current version of the ESA65B letter and will take all of their feedback into account when revising it.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","228790","2019-03-13T16:02:47.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082316/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082316/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 30 May 2018 to Question 146988 on the revised wording of the ESA65B letters sent to employment support allowance claimants’ GPs, on what date the meeting took place at which the British Medical Association and the Royal College of General Practitioners agreed to that revised wording.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","228789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082317","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-12","<p>Costs for how much each National Health Service trust spent in legal fees defending employment tribunal cares relating to discrimination, unfair dismissal and public interest disclosure since 2016 is not held centrally.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-03-12T12:42:06.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082317/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082317/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","NHS Trusts: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much each NHS trust spent on legal fees defending employment tribunal cases relating to (a) discrimination, (b) unfair dismissal and (c) public interest disclosure in each year since 2016.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","228644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082318","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-13","<p>The British Medical Association and the Royal College of General Practitioners agreed to the revised wording of the ESA65B on 4 August 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is committed to ensuring all of its communications are clear, accurate and understandable and we continuously improve our letters. We engage regularly with the welfare benefits advice sector and disability charities and take into account all of the feedback we receive.</p><p> </p><p>We have received comments from a number of sources including MPs, stakeholder organisations and GPs on the current version of the ESA65B letter and will take all of their feedback into account when revising it.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","228789","2019-03-13T16:02:47.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082318/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082318/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if her Department will consult the welfare benefits advice sector and disability charities on the wording of the ESA65B letter to claimants’ GPs after a Work Capability Assessment that finds them fit for work.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","228790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082319","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-12","<p>The counts and rates of Escherichia coli (E. coli) bacteraemia (bloodstream infection) cases reported by National Health Service acute trusts in England are given in the following table.</p><p> </p><p>E. coli bacteraemia counts by financial year, England: 2012/13 to 2017/18</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>All reported E. coli bacteraemia cases</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>32,309</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>34,286</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>35,812</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>38,288</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>40,630</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>41,060</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>Source:</li></ol><p>Annual epidemiological commentary: Gram-negative bacteraemia, Meticillin-Resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) bacteraemia, Meticillin-Sensitive Staphylococcus aureus (MSSA) bacteraemia and C. difficile infections, up to and including financial year April 2017 to March 2018</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/724030/Annual_epidemiological_commentary_2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/724030/Annual_epidemiological_commentary_2018.pdf</a></p><p> </p><ol start="2"><li>Since the mid-2000s onwards, E. coli has been the major cause of bacteraemia. Given the increase in the number of E. coli bacteraemia reports made through the voluntary surveillance programme, the Department made reporting of E. coli bacteraemia by NHS acute trusts mandatory in June 2011.</li></ol><p> </p><p>Data prior to financial year 2012/13 are not available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-03-12T12:25:22.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082319/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082319/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","E. Coli","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people have been diagnosed with E. coli in each financial year for which data are available since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","228743"
