"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082350","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-11","<p>​As I explained in a Statement to the House on 7 March, the British Government is in regular contact with both countries, urging dialogue and diplomatic solutions to ensure regional stability. We are working closely with international partners to de-escalate tensions.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-03-11T17:05:58.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082350/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082350/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-05","Kashmir: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to help resolve tensions in Kashmir; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","228758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082351","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-11","<p>​The British Government is in regular contact with both countries, urging dialogue and diplomatic solutions to ensure regional stability. I welcome both countries publicly stating they do not want to escalate tensions further and their willingness to work with, and through, the international community. On Wednesday 27 February, I spoke to the Indian and Pakistan High Commissioners and pressed the importance of de-escalation. During a pre-arranged visit to India on 1-3 March, I discussed with Foreign Secretary Gokhale steps to decrease tension and improve regional stability, including vital efforts to tackle terrorism. I made a Statement to the House on this subject on 7 March.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-03-11T17:07:12.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082351/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082351/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-05","Kashmir: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in (a) India and (b) Pakistan on the situation in Kashmir; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","228759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082352","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-11","<p>​I recognise that there are deeply held human rights concerns in India-administered and in Pakistan-administered Kashmir. We encourage both India and Pakistan to uphold their international human rights obligations. Any allegations of human rights violations or abuses is concerning and must be investigated thoroughly, promptly and transparently. The UK regularly raises human rights concerns with counterparts in India and Pakistan.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-03-11T17:08:31.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082352/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082352/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-05","Kashmir: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to support the maintenance of the human rights of people in Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","228760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082353","Home Office","false","2019-03-11","<p>We do not hold the data requested.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-03-11T17:01:27.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082353/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082353/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","British Nationals Abroad: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK nationals were deported by another country to the UK in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","228651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082354","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-11","<p>The Government continues to agree the terms of our departure from the EU and continues to plan for all scenarios. It remains committed to consulting on the UK Shared Prosperity Fund. This will give all interested parties the chance to inform final decisions on the Fund, which are due to be taken at the spending review.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2019-03-11T16:51:08.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082354/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082354/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-05","UK Shared Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, for what reasons the public consultation on the UK Shared Prosperity Fund has been delayed.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","228587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082355","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-12","<p>We recognise the challenges for customers who cannot access our online services. We will have a choice of other channels available including assisted digital where customers can ask for assistance from friends, family or other organisations, or by contacting DWP by phone or face to face.</p><p> </p><p>We expect to increase this digital uptake over time, but are aware that we need to keep these channels open during and after our transition to digital.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2019-03-12T11:41:28.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082355/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082355/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082355/answer/previousversion/106857","Biography information for Sarah Newton","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Social Security Benefits: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to written statement HCWS1376, what steps she is taking to ensure that the benefits of a single digital platform are extended to claimants who do not have access to computers or the internet.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","228588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082356","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-11","<p>Vacant properties are not in the interest of tenants, landlords or communities. That is why at Autumn Budget 2018, as part of Our Plan for the High Street, we committed to piloting a register of empty commercial properties and supporting communities to make use of empty properties as part of broad plans for the regeneration of our high streets and town centres. The Housing, Communities and Local Government Select Committee’s inquiry into High Streets and Town Centres in 2030, made a recommendation to review existing policy on vacant commercial properties. The Government is considering the recommendation and will publish our response to the Select Committee in due course.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2019-03-11T16:50:09.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082356/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082356/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-05","Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of empowering local authorities to penalise landlords of commercial properties that are left vacant for lengthy periods of time.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","228589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082357","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-03-11","<p>RAF personnel on secondment to BAE Systems in Saudi Arabia have provided routine engineering support for UK-supplied aircraft operated by the Royal Saudi Air Force (RSAF), including aircraft engaged in military operations in Yemen.</p><p> </p><p>Seconded RAF personnel with BAE Systems have also provided generic training support to RSAF aircrew. The subsequent utilisation of trained RSAF aircrew is not monitored by or otherwise confirmed to the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The above support does not involve the loading of weapons for operational sorties, nor does it include any involvement in the planning of operational sorties.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-03-11T17:56:29.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082357/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082357/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-03-05","Saudi Arabia: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether any RAF personnel on secondment to BAE Systems in Saudi Arabia have (a) maintained Royal Saudi Air Force planes engaged in military operations in Yemen and (b) trained Royal Saudi Air Force personnel engaged in military operations in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","228761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082358","Treasury","false","2019-03-11","<p>The table below shows the full time equivalent (FTE) staff in Solicitor’s Office and Legal Services on 31 March for each financial year since 2010.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FTE</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>367.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>347.17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>348.67</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>370.89</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>373.68</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>397.11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>996.76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>1032.00</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In April 2016 internal restructuring saw our Operational Appeals and Reviews Units merge with our Solicitor’s Office to bring all HMRC litigation activity into one business area.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-03-11T17:15:41.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082358/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082358/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-05","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff were employed in HMRC's Office of the General Counsel and Solicitor in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","228762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082359","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-11","<p>The Government considers the rents paid by tenants of commercial property to be an individual commercial decision between the landlord and tenant. We do not currently have any plans to intervene in such decisions so as not to restrict growth, distort the market or cause other unintended impacts. The Housing, Communities and Local Government Select Committee’s inquiry into High Streets and Town Centres in 2030, made a recommendation to review upwards only rent reviews. The Government is considering this recommendation and will publish our response to the Select Committee in due course.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2019-03-11T16:44:02.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082359/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082359/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-05","Business Premises: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of Government intervention in the retail and hospitality sectors to minimise the number of businesses that pay above-market rents.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","228590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082360","Home Office","false","2019-03-11","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the safety and security of UK and EU citizens. Our intention remains to establish a comprehensive and legally binding agreement on internal security which would enable continuing cooperation based on EU measures.</p><p>However, we are preparing for all eventualities. In a no-deal scenario, UK law enforcement agencies will use well-established alternative mechanisms to co-operate with partners on a police-to-police basis. This will include use of the INTERPOL secure network and pre-existing bi-lateral channels to facilitate police cooperation on child abduction cases.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-03-11T16:18:14.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082360/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082360/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Abduction: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU without a deal on the ability of UK police to deal with child abduction cases.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","228591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082361","Department for Education","false","2019-03-11","<p>Successful applications for wave 13 of the free schools programme will be announced in spring 2019.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-03-11T14:10:42.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082361/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082361/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when he plans to announce the successful applicants for Wave 13 of the Free School programme.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","228763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082362","Department for Education","false","2019-03-11","<p>The National College for High Speed Rail has been established to help provide the skills and qualifications required by High Speed 2 (HS2) and the modern rail industry as a whole. The college offers a range of qualifications, particularly at Level 4 and above, such as apprenticeships, certificates in higher education and foundation degrees via full time and part time delivery. There is no mandatory requirement for any student to be employed by HS2 once they have obtained their qualification. Qualifications and skills gained by students allow them to work for a wide range of organisations in the rail sector.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2019-03-11T16:36:58.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082362/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082362/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether all graduates of the National College for High Speed Rail will be required to work on the High Speed 2 project for a length of time after they graduate.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","228533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082363","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-13","<p>Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is not based on condition or on whether it is or isn’t lifelong, it instead is based on daily living or mobility needs. On 31<sup>st</sup> October 2018, there were 1,430 Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claims in payment that were in receipt of an ongoing award in the Brighton and Hove Local Authority area and 412,070 that were in receipt of an ongoing award in Great Britain.</p><p> </p><p>Ongoing awards do not have an end date, but will be subject to a light touch review at the 10 year point. We have recently amended the guidance to ensure that all those awarded the highest level of support under PIP, and who have needs which will stay the same or deteriorate, will receive an ongoing award with a light touch review at the 10 year point.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Source: PIP ADS</strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ul><li>An ongoing award is defined as an award which has a blank end date in the PIP ADS.</li><li>Figures are based on the latest outcome for each case and will take into account the effect of a Mandatory Reconsideration, an Appeal, Award Review or Change of Circumstances on a claim.</li><li>Normal Rules only</li><li>Data has been rounded to the nearest 10.</li><li>This is unpublished data. It should be used with caution and it may be subject to future revision.</li></ul>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2019-03-13T15:54:09.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082363/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082363/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Personal Independence Payment: Chronic Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in receipt of personal independence payment who are known to have lifelong conditions which are unlikely to improve have been awarded an ongoing award (a) in Brighton and Hove and (b) nationally.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","228652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082364","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-13","<p>Once someone has been awarded Personal Independence Payment (PIP), which can be paid at one of eight rates, that award will be reviewed. Reviews of PIP are a key part of the benefit to ensure that awards remain correct where needs may change and that we maintain contact with the claimant, both features that are missing from its predecessor Disability Living Allowance. The length of an award is based on an individual’s circumstances and can vary from nine months to an on-going award, with a light touch review after ten years.</p><p>We introduced updated guidance for case managers and an updated PIP Assessment Guide in 2018 which will ensure that those people who receive the highest level of support under PIP, and where their needs are unlikely to change or may get worse, will now receive an ongoing award with a light touch review at the ten-year point. In line with PIP’s aim to be needs-based rather than condition-based, the change to the guidance is not condition specific. However, we believe the changes will ensure that those with severe and/or progressive conditions receive the most appropriate award duration that reflects their condition and the needs arising.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2019-03-13T15:39:10.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082364/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082364/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Personal Independence Payment: Chronic Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will make it her policy to end regular reviews of personal independence payment for claimants of working age with (a) motor neurone disease, (b) other degenerative conditions and (c) lifelong conditions which are unlikely to improve; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","228653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082365","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-12","<p>The data requested is not available in the format requested.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-03-12T12:26:47.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082365/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082365/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","General Practitioners: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many GPs are registered in the Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","228654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082366","Department for Education","false","2019-03-13","<p>The institutional autonomy of English Higher Education (HE) providers is protected by the Higher Education and Research Act 2017. This includes autonomy over which courses to offer and which students to admit. The role of government is to create the right conditions and incentives so that HE providers are able to help respond to our economic and strategic priorities. We also want to enable students to make informed choices, and for student demand to influence the decisions providers make on what to offer.</p><p>In England, we agree that learning foreign language is important and believe that building the skills and demand for degree courses starts in schools. That is why we are taking a number of steps to support schools in encouraging uptake of language qualifications.</p><p>This includes:</p><ul><li>Introducing the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) performance measure in 2010 to halt the decline in the number of pupils taking GCSEs in the core academic subjects. The reformed national curriculum now makes it compulsory for pupils in maintained schools to be taught a foreign language in key stage 2.</li><li>Promoting the value of language qualifications to students who are choosing their GCSEs and to their parents. We recently published and promoted a guidance leaflet for parents, which explains why studying a language, as part of the EBacc, broadens opportunities in both education and employment. Additionally, in February we drew attention to the benefits of studying a language among 13-14 year olds through a social media campaign.</li><li>Supporting schools to increase languages take up through the £10 million Mandarin Excellence Programme and through a £4.8 million modern foreign languages pedagogy pilot programme, which will improve uptake and attainment in languages at key stages 3 to 4, particularly for disadvantaged pupils.</li></ul>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-03-13T16:56:43.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082366/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082366/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Languages: Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to help halt the decline in people studying modern languages at university.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","228655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082367","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-03-13","<p>I refer the Hon member to the answer given to PQ 218152 from 20th February.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-03-13T14:11:48.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082367/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082367/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-03-05","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many members of staff in his Department are working full-time on preparation for an adequacy assessment by the European Commission following the UK's withdrawal from the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","228764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082368","Home Office","false","2019-03-13","<p>The Home Office does not hold information that is broken down in this way, and it could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2019-03-13T16:15:55.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082368/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082368/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Law and Order: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff of his Department are working on programmes relating to UK-EU law enforcement information-sharing following the UK's withdrawal from the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","228765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082369","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-11","<p>The level and appropriateness of car parking charges at National Health Service sites is the responsibility of the local NHS trust. We have published the NHS Car Parking Principles which clearly state that concessions should be offered to groups who most need help, such as staff who cannot travel by public transport due to their shift pattern.</p><p> </p><p>However, given it is the responsibility of the local NHS trust, the Department has no jurisdiction to reduce or eliminate hospital car parking charges for nurses, doctors and essential healthcare workers.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-03-11T17:11:49.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082369/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082369/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans he has to reduce or eliminate hospital car parking charges for nurses, doctors and essential healthcare workers.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","228543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082370","Department for Exiting the European Union ","true","2019-03-11","<p>From the very beginning the Prime Minister has been clear that safeguarding the rights of EU citizens living in the UK and UK nationals living in the EU was her first priority for negotiations. The best way to guarantee those rights, both for UK nationals in the EU and EU citizens in the UK, is through the Withdrawal Agreement.</p><p>On 27 February, the House of Commons supported a proposal by Alberto Costa MP which requires the Government to seek a joint UK/EU commitment to preserve the citizens’ rights section of the Withdrawal Agreement, whatever the outcome of negotiations.</p><p><del class="ministerial">The Secretary of State Steve Barclay has now written to the EU’s lead Brexit negotiator Michel Barnier, on ring-fencing the Citizens’ Rights part of the Withdrawal Agreement. This letter has also been copied to Guy Verhofstadt, the European Parliament’s Brexit coordinator and shared with the Secretary-General. Copies of the letter have been placed in the libraries of both Houses and it has been published online at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/costa-amendment-letter-to-the-eu-institutions" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Secretary of State Steve Barclay has now written to the EU’s lead Brexit negotiator Michel Barnier, on ring-fencing the Citizens’ Rights part of the Withdrawal Agreement. This letter has also been shared with Guy Verhofstadt, the European Parliament’s Brexit coordinator and the Secretary General of the European Council. Copies of the letter have been placed in the libraries of both Houses and it has been published online at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/costa-amendment-letter-to-the-eu-institutions" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2019-03-11T16:50:27.41Z","2019-03-11T21:37:11.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082370/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082370/answer","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082370/answer/previousversion/106785","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-03-05","Free Movement of People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether the Prime Minister has entered into correspondence with the European Council on changing the mandate of the European Commission to allow for the adoption of part two of the Withdrawal Agreement on citizens’ rights under Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","228559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082371","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-12","<p>Every sustainability and transformation plan was published by the end of 2016 and these can be found through NHS England’s website at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/integratedcare/stps/view-stps" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/integratedcare/stps/view-stps</a></p><p>Local leaders drawing up these proposals were asked to consider local challenges and priorities, with workforce a key priority. During 2019, each local system will refresh its plan.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-03-12T12:45:04.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082371/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082371/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Sustainability and Transformation Partnerships: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many sustainability and transformation plans that have been produced included a workforce plan within them.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","228766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082372","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-11","<p>The decision to close a court is never taken lightly. Court closures have taken place following a public consultation and only when the Lord Chancellor was satisfied that effective access to justice could be maintained. We have closed less efficient courts allowing for resources to be concentrated into a smaller number of better quality and more flexible buildings.</p><p> </p><p>The table below provides a list of courts closed in the 2010/11 financial year, their date of sale and the disposal proceeds.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Courts and tribunals closed during 2010-2011 financial year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Date sold</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proceeds</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wantage Magistrates’ Court</p></td><td><p>Jan-16</p></td><td><p>657,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Please note the list does not include court integrations.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-03-11T17:46:19.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082372/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082372/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-05","Courts: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which courts his Department closed in 2010; on what dates those court buildings were sold; and what the value was of those sales.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","228767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082373","Department for International Trade","false","2019-03-11","<p>All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes Official Statistics (on a quarterly and annual basis) about export licences granted, refused and revoked on GOV.UK. These reports contain detailed information on export licences issued, refused or revoked, by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences. These can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data." target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data.</a></p><p>The data currently provides details of licences up to 30 September 2018. Information about the period 1 October to 31 December 2018 will be published on 16 April 2019 and data covering the period 1 January 2019 to 31 March 2019 will be published in July 2019.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-03-11T15:52:37.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082373/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082373/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-03-05","Arms Trade: Turkey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the value has been of UK arms export licences to Turkey issued in each of the last five calendar years.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","228768"
