"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082383","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-13","<p>The table below provides a list of courts closed in the 2018/ 19 financial year as at the end of February 2019.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Operational Court building closures 2018/19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proceeds (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chippenham Magistrates' &amp; Civil Court</p></td><td><p>Disposal pending</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chichester Combined Court</p></td><td><p>Disposal pending</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Maidenhead Magistrates’ Court</p></td><td><p>Disposal pending</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>To note, the list does not include court integrations, which involve the movement of (or merging) of services into another existing HMCTS location in the same local area.</p><p> </p><p>The closure of any court is not taken lightly – it only happens following full public consultation and when communities have reasonable access to alternative courts.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-03-13T17:23:53.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082383/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082383/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-05","Courts: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which courts his Department closed in 2018; on what dates those court buildings were sold; and what the value was of each of those sales.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","228778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082384","Home Office","false","2019-03-11","<p>Sector level information is not collected on a mandatory basis by the DBS as part of its checks, therefore it is not possible to provide or assess this information.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-03-11T16:24:55.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082384/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082384/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Vetting: Social Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps he is taking to reduce the time taken to process DBS checks for potential care workers.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","228779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082385","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-13","<p>The Government has two Ministers with responsibility for human rights. In my role as Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Ministry of Justice, I have Ministerial responsibility for human rights domestically, and Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon, Minister of State for the Commonwealth and the United Nations at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, has responsibility for human rights internationally.</p><p> </p><p>We have no plans for additional Human Rights Ministers or Commissioners.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-03-13T17:48:22.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082385/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082385/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-05","Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Government has any plans to promote human rights in the UK and abroad through the creation of a dedicated UK Minister or commissioner for human rights.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","228780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082386","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-11","<p>We do not collect information for primary medical care practices about the cost of providing care to individual patients or cohorts of patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-03-11T18:24:06.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082386/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082386/answer","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082386/answer/previousversion/106919","Biography information for Steve Brine","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the average annual cost to a GP's surgery is of providing NHS GP funding formula funded primary care to someone between the ages of 20 to 49 years old.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","228781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082387","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-03-11","<p>The Government has undertaken extensive work to identify the primary legislation essential to deliver our exit from the EU in different scenarios.</p><p>Much of this legislation is already in place, for example The Taxation (Cross-border Trade) Act, The Nuclear Safeguards Act and the Haulage Permits and Trailer Registration Act, and a number of important statutory instruments.</p><p>The Government is confident that we will have all the necessary legislation in place by exit day.</p><p /> <p><strong></strong><br><br></p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng",,"2019-03-11T09:45:22.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082387/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082387/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-03-05","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what Bills need to be passed by Parliament by 29 March 2019 in order for the UK to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Dominic Grieve","Beaconsfield","Mr Dominic Grieve","228530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082388","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-03-11","<p>The length of time required for the full implementation of all EU-exit related Acts of Parliament will depend on the specific nature of each Act.</p><p>The Government is confident that we will have all the necessary legislation in place by Exit Day.</p><p> </p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng",,"2019-03-11T09:46:22.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082388/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082388/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-03-05","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate the Government has made of the length of time required for the full implementation of all EU-exit related Acts of Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mr Dominic Grieve","Beaconsfield","Mr Dominic Grieve","228531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082389","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-03-11","<p>Over 480 exit related statutory instruments (80% of the up to 600 expected by exit day) have been laid. <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/votes-and-proceedings/#session=29&amp;year=2019&amp;month=2&amp;day=5" target="_blank">Votes and Proceedings</a> provides the lists of SIs that have been approved by the House.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-03-11T12:17:18.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082389/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082389/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-03-05","Brexit: Statutory Instruments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many EU-exit related statutory instruments have been approved.","false","Biography information for Mr Dominic Grieve","Beaconsfield","Mr Dominic Grieve","228534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082390","Department for Education","false","2019-03-11","<p>The department published statutory guidance in April 2013 that sets out clearly what local authorities must do to meet the legal requirements in section 5 of the Childcare Act (2006), which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centres" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centres</a>. This includes guidance on advisory boards and facilitating access to services for young children and their families. It is up to local authorities to decide exactly how to meet these legal requirements depending on local circumstances.</p><p>The department is engaging with the sector to find out ‘what works’ and to support local areas to make the right decisions for their communities. We are investing £8.5 million in a local government programme to spread good practice, grow the evidence base and help councils looking to improve outcomes for disadvantaged children and their peers. Good practice from this programme will include, but not be limited to, how children’s centres are being used to deliver effective integrated early childhood services.</p><p>We will be spending around £6 billion a year on childcare support in 2019-20 – a record amount. This includes funding for our free early education entitlements, on which we plan to spend around £3.5 billion this year alone.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","228783","2019-03-11T14:16:23.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082390/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082390/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Children's Centres: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when a review of the operation of section 5C (Children's centres: advisory boards) Childcare Act 2006 was last undertaken; and if he will publish good practice on the operation of Advisory Boards.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","228782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082391","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-03-11","<p>The Government expects to make up to 600 statutory instruments by exit day.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-03-11T09:44:01.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082391/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082391/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-03-05","Brexit: Statutory Instruments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate the Government has made of the number of EU-exit related statutory instruments that are required to be approved by 29 March.","false","Biography information for Mr Dominic Grieve","Beaconsfield","Mr Dominic Grieve","228535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082392","Department for Education","false","2019-03-11","<p>The department published statutory guidance in April 2013 that sets out clearly what local authorities must do to meet the legal requirements in section 5 of the Childcare Act (2006), which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centres" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centres</a>. This includes guidance on advisory boards and facilitating access to services for young children and their families. It is up to local authorities to decide exactly how to meet these legal requirements depending on local circumstances.</p><p>The department is engaging with the sector to find out ‘what works’ and to support local areas to make the right decisions for their communities. We are investing £8.5 million in a local government programme to spread good practice, grow the evidence base and help councils looking to improve outcomes for disadvantaged children and their peers. Good practice from this programme will include, but not be limited to, how children’s centres are being used to deliver effective integrated early childhood services.</p><p>We will be spending around £6 billion a year on childcare support in 2019-20 – a record amount. This includes funding for our free early education entitlements, on which we plan to spend around £3.5 billion this year alone.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","228782","2019-03-11T14:16:23.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082392/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082392/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Sure Start Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans he has to ensure that children in their first 1001 days have access to Sure Start services.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","228783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082396","Treasury","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Basic PAYE Tool (BPT) is a downloadable tool which HMRC has made available, at no cost to the customer, to enable small employers to run their payrolls in compliance with the PAYE legislation. Information on the number of employers who use the BPT is not readily accessible and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2019-03-19T15:31:10.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082396/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082396/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-05","PAYE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many employers use the HMRC Basic PAYE tool for their payroll data calculations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL14233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082397","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-12","<p>We interpret the question to be referring to the Basic Assessment Tool spreadsheet data, which started in September 2015.</p><p>From 2015 to the end of 2018, the Pensions Regulator’s Basic Assessment Tool was downloaded a total of 6,776 times. The table below provides a breakdown of downloads in each year.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Downloads</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>74</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>4176</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>2268</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>258</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2019-03-12T16:16:59.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082397/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082397/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Occupational Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many downloads of the Pensions Regulator assessment calculation spreadsheet there have been in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL14234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082398","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-12","<p>I refer the noble Baroness to my answer of 12th November 2018.</p><p>Employers, trustees, managers and providers must keep certain records including details of the pension contributions payable in each relevant pay reference period by an employer to the scheme, and the amount payable. This includes the contributions due on the employer’s behalf and deductions made from an individual’s earnings.</p><p>The Pensions Regulator has published codes of practice on its website setting out how trustees of defined contribution pension schemes and managers of personal pension schemes should monitor the payment of contributions, provide information to help members check their contributions and report material payment failures to The Pensions Regulator. However, The Pensions Regulator does not hold statistics on contribution data errors. The Pensions Regulator have payment failure reports from pension providers but these do not necessarily represent data errors.</p><p>In addition, The Pensions Regulator publishes regular assessments of its automatic enrolment compliance and enforcement activities as well as an annual commentary and analysis report, both of which are available on its website.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2019-03-12T16:35:55.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082398/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082398/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-05","Occupational Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what evidence and statistics they hold in relation to automatic enrolment pension contribution data errors.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL14235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082399","Treasury","false","2019-03-19","<p>Errors made by employers and pension providers have resulted in individuals receiving either no tax relief on their pension contributions, or receiving tax relief twice.</p><p> </p><p>In the Pension schemes newsletter 105 (November 2018), HMRC invited pension schemes who think that any of their members have been given the wrong amount of tax relief to email HMRC. HMRC would then work with them to help correct their tax position.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is working with pension schemes and can’t give more detail of the dealing of these cases as this could prejudice future compliance activity.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2019-03-19T13:10:54.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082399/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082399/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-05","Occupational Pensions: Tax Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many employers have been asked to repay overpaid tax relief as a result of employers submitting pension contributions which incorrectly based their payments on the wrong assumption about whether the pension scheme used Relief at Source or Net Pay for administering tax relief.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL14236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082400","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Government's statement of 27 February recognises that Nigerians have expressed concerns about the conduct of the Nigerian elections, in particular in relation to logistics, results collation and reports of intimidation of election officials. We are encouraging the Nigerian authorities to examine all allegations of wrongdoing carefully and take action against individuals found responsible. Our statement also recognises the importance of people being able to vote safely and expresses condolences to the families and friends of those killed in election related violence. We will continue to support Nigeria and its civil society in drawing lessons from these elections and strengthening its democracy.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-03-19T16:15:07.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082400/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082400/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-05","Nigeria: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the statement by the Nigerian pro-democracy group, the Mandate Protection Vanguard that the UK Prime Minister’s congratulatory message to the Nigerian President on his electoral victory failed to address (1) voter suppression in opposition strongholds, (2) abductions and intimidation of electoral officials, (3) the destruction of ballot boxes, (4) assaults on voters by members of the security services and others, (5) organised mass thumb-printing of ballot papers, including by minors, and (6) the deaths of at least 39 people in election related violence.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL14237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082401","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The British High Commissioner has urged the Nigerian Government and the Nigerian Independent National Elections Commission (INEC) to address the concerns raised by Nigerians about the conduct of the Presidential elections so that the Gubernatorial elections can proceed in accordance with Nigerian electoral legislation. The Minister for Africa has reiterated these messages in a phone call to the Nigerian Foreign Minister.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-03-19T16:13:19.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082401/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082401/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-05","Nigeria: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following reports that Nigeria’s recent presidential and national assembly elections were marred by violence and allegations of electoral fraud, what representations they will make to the government of Nigeria about ensuring free, fair and peaceful gubernatorial elections are held on 9 May.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL14238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082402","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>We have made representations to the Nigerian authorities to act on the court order mandating release of Ibrahim El-Zakzaky and his wife, Zeenah Ibraham. We have not made representations regarding Sambo Dasuki. The Rule of Law is critical in any country, as it is in Nigeria. We encourage the government to uphold the rule of law and ensure due process is followed.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-03-19T16:12:56.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082402/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082402/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-05","Nigeria: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Nigeria about the wellbeing of (1) Sambo Dasuki, (2) Sheikh Ibrahim Zakzaky, and (3) Zeenah Ibrahim, who have been detained since 2015 despite court orders for their release.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL14239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082403","Home Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The UK supports UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 2396 and the associated Madrid Guiding Principles, and contributed to the drafting of both. We encourage Member States to fully implement UNSCR 2396.</p><p>We work with a number of multilateral bodies such as UN, Global Counter Terrorism Forum, and the Global Coalition against Daesh amongst others.</p><p>The Government published its updated counter-terrorism strategy, CONTEST, in June 2018. As the Home Secretary set out, it is through working together, with the police, security and intelligence agencies, the private and public sectors, civil society, international partners, and the public, that we will reduce the risk of terrorism and ensure that terrorists cannot and will not change our way of life</p><p><br>A joint Home Office and DCMS White Paper will be published shortly, setting out a range of legislative and non-legislative measures detailing how we will tackle online harms and set clear responsibilities for technology companies to keep UK citizens safe. The White Paper will set out how we expect companies to provide support to law enforcement where relevant.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL14241","2019-03-19T17:07:13.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082403/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082403/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Terrorism: Criminal Investigation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of recommendations in the Addendum to the 2015 Madrid Guiding Principle 9(28)(e) to "enhance cooperation between the relevant investigative agencies, including police-to-police and with the private sector, especially with information and communications technologies service providers, in gathering digital data and evidence in cases relating to terrorism and foreign terrorist fighters".","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL14240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082404","Home Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The UK supports UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 2396 and the associated Madrid Guiding Principles, and contributed to the drafting of both. We encourage Member States to fully implement UNSCR 2396.</p><p>We work with a number of multilateral bodies such as UN, Global Counter Terrorism Forum, and the Global Coalition against Daesh amongst others.</p><p>The Government published its updated counter-terrorism strategy, CONTEST, in June 2018. As the Home Secretary set out, it is through working together, with the police, security and intelligence agencies, the private and public sectors, civil society, international partners, and the public, that we will reduce the risk of terrorism and ensure that terrorists cannot and will not change our way of life</p><p><br>A joint Home Office and DCMS White Paper will be published shortly, setting out a range of legislative and non-legislative measures detailing how we will tackle online harms and set clear responsibilities for technology companies to keep UK citizens safe. The White Paper will set out how we expect companies to provide support to law enforcement where relevant.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL14240","2019-03-19T17:07:13.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082404/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082404/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Terrorism: Criminal Investigation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of recommendations in the Addendum to the 2015 Madrid Guiding Principle 9(28)(f) to "request and gather electronic evidence from the relevant actors and across borders and consider making use of the Practical Guide for Requesting Electronic Evidence Across Borders developed by the Counter-Terrorism Committee Executive Directorate, UN Office on Drugs and Crime and the International Association of Prosecutors".","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL14241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082405","Home Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Government welcomes the Addendum to the 2015 Madrid Guiding Principles. In 2018 the UK’s counter-terrorist financing regime received the highest possible rating in a review by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF). As set out in FATF’s report on the review, I can confirm that the police routinely and systematically conduct a financial investigation when investigating terrorism cases.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-03-19T16:44:26.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082405/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082405/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Terrorism: Criminal Investigation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of recommendations in the Addendum to the 2015 Madrid Guiding Principle 10(29)(c) to "Conduct systematic financial investigations in all terrorism cases".","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL14242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082406","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-13","<p>The Secretary of State had a range of meetings with officials, Ministers, agencies and MPs on Monday 4 and Tuesday 5 March.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2019-03-13T15:39:18.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082406/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082406/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-05","Chris Grayling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which appointments and visits were arranged for the Secretary of State for Transport for (1) 4 March, and (2) 5 March.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL14243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082407","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-15","<p>The following table shows the respective cumulative increase in NHS England's revenue funding, excluding depreciation, for the next five financial years as compared to the 2018/19 financial year, final settlement, cash terms.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2019-20</p></td><td><p>2020-21</p></td><td><p>2021-22</p></td><td><p>2022-23</p></td><td><p>2023-24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£6.2 billion</p></td><td><p>£12.4 billion</p></td><td><p>£18.7 billion</p></td><td><p>£25.4 billion</p></td><td><p>£33.9 billion</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-03-15T11:30:44.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082407/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082407/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","NHS: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what will be the increase to the current year's NHS budget in each of the next five financial years.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL14244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082408","Department for Education","false","2019-03-15","<p>Three organisations were invited to bid for the contract to draft the model music curriculum; the Associated Board of the Royal Schools of Music (ABRSM), the Incorporated Society of Musicians, and Music Mark. ABRSM made an application, the other two organisations did not bid.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2019-03-15T14:29:36.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082408/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082408/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Music: Curriculum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which organisations were (1) asked to, and (2) did, bid for the contract to draft the new model music curriculum.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL14245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082409","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-15","<p>There are no current plans to make bio-identical hormone replacement therapy routinely available on National Health Service prescription. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) is the Agency responsible for the regulation of medicines used in the United Kingdom. There is a clear regime in place, administered by the MHRA, to enable medicines to be developed, authorised (licensed) and made available to patients in the UK. It is important that authorised medicines meet rigorous standards so that doctors and patients are sure of their quality, efficacy and safety.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-03-15T11:28:30.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082409/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082409/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-05","Hormone Replacement Therapy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to provide for the prescription of bio-identical hormone replacement therapy as part of NHS treatment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL14246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082410","Home Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The UK supports UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 2396 and the associated Madrid Guiding Principles, and contributed to the drafting of both. We encourage Member States to fully implement UNSCR 2396.</p><p>We work with a number of multilateral bodies such as UN, Global Counter Terrorism Forum, and the Global Coalition against Daesh amongst others.</p><p>The Government published its updated counter-terrorism strategy, CONTEST, in July 2018. As the Home Secretary set out, it is through working together, with the police, security and intelligence agencies, the private and public sectors, civil society, international partners, and the public, that we will reduce the risk of terrorism and ensure that terrorists cannot and will not change our way of life.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-03-19T17:15:16.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082410/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082410/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of (1) Guiding Principle 11(30)(a), (2) Guiding Principle 11(30)(b), (3) Guiding Principle 11(30)(c), (4) Guiding Principle 11(30)(f), and (5) Guiding Principle 11(30)(j), as set out in the 2018 Addendum to the 2015 Madrid Guiding Principles.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL14247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082411","Home Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The UK supports UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 2396 and the associated Madrid Guiding Principles, and contributed to the drafting of both. We encourage Member States to fully implement UNSCR 2396.</p><p>We work with a number of multilateral bodies such as UN, Global Counter Terrorism Forum, and the Global Coalition against Daesh amongst others.</p><p>The Government published its updated counter-terrorism strategy, CONTEST, in July 2018. As the Home Secretary set out, it is through working together, with the police, security and intelligence agencies, the private and public sectors, civil society, international partners, and the public, that we will reduce the risk of terrorism and ensure that terrorists cannot and will not change our way of life</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-03-19T17:15:04.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082411/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082411/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-05","Terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of Guiding Principle 9(28)(c) as set out in the 2018 Addendum to the 2015 Madrid Guiding Principles.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL14248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082412","Department for Education","false","2019-03-18","<p>The department is actively engaged in the situation at Parkfield Community School, where parents are objecting to an educational programme, No Outsiders, which contains elements of teaching around lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender issues. Senior officials from the Regional School Commissioner’s Office have been on site regularly since the start of this issue and have facilitated conversations between the community, the academy and Excelsior Multi Academy Trust. They are already working closely with the right hon. Member for Birmingham, Hodge Hill, Birmingham City Council and Birmingham Education Partnership to resolve the conflict and, as such, end pupil absences as soon as possible.</p><p>At this stage the department believes no extra provision is required, however every extra day of school missed can have a negative impact on pupils’ education; there must therefore be a good reason to take them out of school. The department is working with the school and its parents to find a solution.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2019-03-18T11:20:16.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082412/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1082412/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-05","Parkfield School Birmingham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following reports that parents have withdrawn their children from Parkfield Community School in Alum Rock, Birmingham, what steps they have taken to ensure that pupils who have been withdrawn receive an adequate education whilst not attending school.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL14249"
